Sorry, but it's impossible to generate the exact Solidity code from the bytecode. The bytecode is the compiled version of the Solidity code and doesn't contain all the information that the original code had, like variable names, comments, function names, etc. 

However, you can attempt to decompile the bytecode to get an assembly-like representation of the code. Tools like Etherscan's contract verification process, or the Solidity Remix IDE, can provide a level of understanding for the bytecode.

But again, this won't give you the original Solidity code. It's always important to have the original Solidity source code available for auditing and understanding the contract's functionality.
